   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28617_1828_08_29_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgworthtown</placeName>, <date when="1828-08-29">
                     <add>Friday night</add> Aug. 29/28</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">wify</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> and I have had this<lb/>
               evening our <hi rend="underline">usual</hi> dispute about the second-<lb/>
               -rate importance, or, the preeminence of memory,<lb/>
               among the faculties of the mind - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                     </orig>
                     <reg>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                     </reg>
                  </choice>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Butler</persName>
               <lb/>
               occasionally joined sometimes on one side<lb/>
               sometimes on the other <del/> and always sensibly<lb/>
               <del>and</del>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">She</persName> supported her argument with<lb/>
               extraordinary ingenuity and with various<lb/>
               amusing &amp; apposite illustrations, for which<lb/>
               take notice she was indebted to the very<lb/>
               faculty that she was underrating. - The<lb/>
               grand question remains in both our views of<lb/>
               the subject - How is the memory to be managed<lb/>
               ? - A good memory to be <unclear>made</unclear> recollection? -<lb/>
               or a bad memory to be assisted. - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> throws<lb/>
               out some useful hints - such as leading <choice>
                  <orig>chil-<lb/>
                  dren</orig>
                  <reg>children</reg>
               </choice> to exercises which require the joint <choice>
                  <orig>combi-<lb/>
                     nation</orig>
                  <reg>combination</reg>
               </choice> of <del>ing</del> invention &amp; memory - as practiced<lb/>
               at his school - Mental arithmetic, where the<lb/>
               child (suppose in multiplying a sum by two figures)<lb/>
               is obliged to have recourse to <hi rend="underline">some means</hi> of recollecting<lb/>
               the multiplicand of the 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. figure in order to<lb/>
               have it ready to add to that of the 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. figure. <del/> It is<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28617_1828_08_29_page02.jpg"/>
               
               a highly interesting subject and I endeavoured<lb/>
               to excite her to put together all the hints she could<lb/>
               collect, and at some future time to tell us all that<lb/>
               can be done to ourselves and to our pupils, instead<lb/>
               of eternally repeating with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ2">Locke</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ReidT1">Reid</persName> and a hundred<lb/>
               others the mere words "Arrange the facts you acquire"<lb/>
               "Connect your ideas by links" "Association is the<lb/>
               grand key to the storehouse of the mind" &amp;c &amp;c<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>How I am running on! <del>though</del> I only alluded<lb/>
               to the subject in order to add that I think I had<lb/>
               good reason to leave off in the same opinion that<lb/>
               I began - and at least to complain of my own<lb/>
               want of this valuable quality as on sitting down<lb/>
               now to write to you I cannot recollect whether<lb/>
               in the letter I dispatched to you from Trim I<lb/>
               entered into any description of my adventures<lb/>
               then amongst the decaying castles convents<lb/>
               and churches of former times. For fear however<lb/>
               of the "hateful twice told tale" I shall pass over<lb/>
               them (trusting to my poor memory to recall the<lb/>
               subject when I have the delight of returning<lb/>
               to your arms and to your ears) and proceed<lb/>
               with my onward journey. - Wednesday at<lb/>
               11 we started from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName> Vicarage, and, along with<lb/>
               us, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Butler</persName> in their carriage. We went by<lb/>
               the pretty <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Killucan_IE">Killucan</placeName> road to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mullingar_IE">Mullingar</placeName> - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Rathoan-Road_IE">Rathoan</placeName> -<lb/>
               where we met the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">
                  <choice>
                     <abbr>Edg<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>.</abbr>
                     <reg>Edgeworth</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> horses and arrived at 5 -<lb/>
                  having drawn in a little to allow <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. <choice>
                     <abbr>B.</abbr>
                     <reg>Butler</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> to form<lb/>
               part of the large group that was assembled on<lb/>
               the lawn to receive <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">Aunt Mary</persName> in the home of<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28617_1828_08_29_page03.jpg"/>
               
               her choice. Some cried <add>some smiled</add> - some were silent and<lb/>
               some talked in full exuberance of heart; - the meeting<lb/>
               was really affectingly pleasing. - The evening<lb/>
               was brilliantly fine and the sun seemed to <hi rend="underline">loiter</hi>
               <lb/>
               over the western hills, for much was yet to be done.<lb/>
               When dark an immense bonfire suddenly blazed<lb/>
               up in front of the house and gave the signal to<lb/>
               the whole population of the town who poured into<lb/>
               the lawn preced<del/>ed by a band of music playing<lb/>
               "Why should <add>old acquaintance be forgotten."</add>
               <del/> The crowd drew up and gave three<lb/>
               cheers - not very harmonious indeed from the <choice>
                  <orig>pre-<lb/>
                  ponderance</orig>
                  <reg>preponderance</reg>
               </choice> of screaming women &amp; shrill children<lb/>
               but given with all their might &amp; heart - This was<lb/>
               repeated and again and again renewed till I began<lb/>
               to feel "How is this to end?" - I therefore suggested<lb/>
               to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> to stand up on the steps and thank<lb/>
               the multitude in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">Aunt Mary</persName>'s name. He took<lb/>
               the hint - and having a made a very decent<lb/>
               speech the people gave another noble yell and m<unclear/>
               <lb/>
               out again with pipe and drum. - All hands that<lb/>
               dared to trust themselves in the dewy breath of Heaven<lb/>
               now walked up the town which was splendidly <choice>
                  <orig>illu-<lb/>
                  minated</orig>
                  <reg>illuminated</reg>
               </choice> - <hi rend="underline">every pane</hi> of every window having a candle<orig/>
               <lb/>
               stuck in it - and every pane had been cleaned that<lb/>
               no twinkle might be lost, and that the laurel, the<lb/>
               oak, the rose and Rose<hi rend="underline">Mary</hi> might be the more conspicuous.<lb/>
               - The street was quite full - parties kept roaring<lb/>
               longlife to K. G. the 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. and the Royal family - <del/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Mister<lb/>
                  Ejowrth</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Mary Sneyd</persName> for ever - and some<lb/>
               wags added And <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OConX2">O'Connel</persName> too. - One of their gambols<lb/>
               was placing a lighted tar barrel on a large slate which<lb/>
               4 men paraded on their shoulders. - Poor <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">Aunt<lb/>
               Mary</persName> indeed the object of all this rude &amp; clamorous<lb/>
               but I do believe sincere effusion of joy, was precluded<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28617_1828_08_29_page04.jpg"/>
               
               from witnessing it - for she was too blind to enjoy the effort - but she heard<lb/>
               in the library frequent reports of what was doing -and she must have been<lb/>
               much more than woman if she did not feel something of the intoxication<lb/>
               of popularity - And who could deserve it better? - Would to Heaven<lb/>
               that the noisy throats of mobs were never strained in a worse cause - in<lb/>
               chusing the licentious despot - in the war howl of welcome to the blood stained<lb/>
               conqueror - or in the acclamation of the wily demagogue who laughs at <add>the</add>
               <choice>
                  <orig>enthusi-<lb/>
                  -asm</orig>
                  <reg>enthusiasm</reg>
               </choice> which he knows how to fire but never felt. - By eleven (the Mail Coach<lb/>
               having passed "&amp; wondered at the work" that was going on) all the <add>Town</add> lights were<lb/>
               out - and the library was filled with 17 happy <del/> people who<lb/>
               again congratulated the excellent heroine of the day, and at length<lb/>
               allowed her to retire to a repose which the termination of a long journey<lb/>
               and the excitement of the evening made necessary. - I must now<lb/>
               and waken <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> who is going in the Mail Coach to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Sligo_IE">Sligo</placeName> on his<lb/>
               way to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Donegal_IE">Donegal</placeName> where he has some Engineering works, and<lb/>
               from whence he came to <unclear>receive</unclear>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">his Aunt</persName> - So Good night<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Saturday. Visitors have begun to pour in<lb/>
                  and from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">A.M.</persName> will be congratulated without<lb/>
               quarter. -  </p>
            <closer>
               <unclear>Heaven</unclear>preserve you <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               <unclear/> for<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">FB</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Beaufort</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#29-Richmond-Place_ENK">Richmond Place 29<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                     </placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Brighton_ENK">Brighton</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
               <note>Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. 29-30 - 1828</note>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
